{"type":"message","id":"1fec7aae","parentId":"eada2c4b","timestamp":"2026-05-02T01:35:10.230Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Two questions from Bobby:\n1. Why so many active sessions (439) and what does it mean?\n2. Confirm we don't need the MC watchdog\n\nLet me answer both.\n\n**Sessions:** The 439 sessions include all cron jobs, sub-agents, and historical sessions. Most of those shown in the status are old/inactive sessions. The \"active\" count is cumulative - it's not 439 concurrent sessions, just a running total of all sessions ever created. The ones that matter are the ones in the Sessions list (current ones, cron sessions, etc.)\n\n**MC Watchdog:** He's right - if MC server is running as a LaunchAgent (which auto-restarts), the watchdog is redundant and can be removed. Let me confirm and offer to clean it up.","thinkingSignature":"9aebe44c8e47f0fd447facd2caf2db70f317153abf863b67b526e06cbe47df42"},{"type":"text","text":"\n\n**439 Sessions:**\n\nMost of those are **historical** sessions — cron jobs, sub-agents, one-off tasks from over time. The system counts all sessions ever created, not concurrent ones.\n\nWhat matters from the status table:\n- **Current Telegram chat** — active right now ✅\n- **Main session** — your main chat context ✅\n- **Cron sessions** — automated jobs that ran recently ✅\n- The OpenAI ones are from older model calls\n\n**TL;DR:** Not a problem. High count is normal over time. ✅\n\n---\n\n**MC Watchdog:** Yeah, you're right — drop it. MC server already runs as a LaunchAgent which auto-starts on boot and auto-restarts on crash. The watchdog is redundant.\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_n2gjpkbg935r_1","name":"cron","arguments":{"action":"list","includeDisabled":true}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":42040,"output":343,"cacheRead":224,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":42607,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite"