{"type":"message","id":"a79bbea2","parentId":"3b054a57","timestamp":"2026-05-02T02:13:49.223Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_uanb15tgwxsp_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"188:    /* ── SECTION PAGES ── */\n469:    /* Section footer */\n578:     SECTION 1: WHAT IS OPENCLAW\n584:    <div class=\"chapter-label\">Section 1</div>\n651:    <p>Section 1 — What is OpenClaw? ✅ Complete</p>\n656:     SECTION 2: WHY OPENCLAW OVER CHATGPT\n662:    <div class=\"chapter-label\">Section 2</div>\n727:    <p>Section 2 — Why OpenClaw Over ChatGPT? ✅ Complete</p>\n732:     SECTION 3: HOW IT HAS BENEFITED ME\n738:    <div class=\"chapter-label\">Section 3</div>\n809:    <p>Section 3 — How OpenClaw Has Benefited Me ✅ Complete</p>\n814:     SECTION 4: THINGS I WISH I KNEW\n820:    <div class=\"chapter-label\">Section 4</div>\n890:    <p>Section 4 — Things I Wish I Knew Before Starting ✅ Complete</p>\n895:     SECTION 5: INSTALLATION & SETUP\n901:    <div class=\"chapter-label\">Section 5</div>\n970:    <p>Section 5 — Installation & Setup ✅ Complete</p>\n975:     SECTION 6: CORE CONCEPTS\n981:    <div class=\"chapter-label\">Section 6</div>\n1039:    <p>Section 6 — Core Concepts ✅ Complete</p>"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":12,"aggregated":"188:    /* ── SECTION PAGES ── */\n469:    /* Section footer */\n578:     SECTION 1: WHAT IS OPENCLAW\n584:    <div class=\"chapter-label\">Section 1</div>\n651:    <p>Section 1 — What is OpenClaw? ✅ Complete</p>\n656:     SECTION 2: WHY OPENCLAW OVER CHATGPT\n662:    <div class=\"chapter-label\">Section 2</div>\n727:    <p>Section 2 — Why OpenClaw Over ChatGPT? ✅ Complete</p>\n732:     SECTION 3: HOW IT HAS BENEFITED ME\n738:    <div class=\"chapter-label\">Section 3</div>\n809:    <p>Section 3 — How OpenClaw Has Benefited Me ✅ Complete</p>\n814:     SECTION 4: THINGS I WISH I KNEW\n820:    <div class=\"chapter-label\">Section 4</div>\n890:    <p>Section 4 — Things I Wish I Knew Before Starting ✅ Complete</p>\n895:     SECTION 5: INSTALLATION & SETUP\n901:    <div class=\"chapter-label\">Section 5</div>\n970:    <p>Section 5 — Installation & Setup ✅ Complete</p>\n975:     SECTION 6: CORE CONCEPTS\n981:    <div class=\"chapter-label\">Section 6</div>\n1039:    <p>Section 6 — Core Concepts ✅ Complete</p>","cwd":"/Users/bobbygalletta/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1777688029223}}
{"type":"message","id":"2def6dc6","parentId":"a79bbea2","timestamp":"2026-05-02T02:13:52.902Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"So the full preview HTML has \"Section 1: What is OpenClaw\" at line 578. Let me look at what's actually in Section 1 of the HTML to see if the Peter Steinberger story is there or not.\n","thinkingSignature":"c13a309d21a46f304339c7b96cebae7c38ccad18e8e679ec2634ed83efe1874b"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_wk3g3jvuvgwt_1","name":"read","arguments":{"limit":60,"offset":580,"path":"/Users/bobbygalletta/Desktop/OpenClaw/OpenClaw-Guide-By-Bobby/The-OpenClaw-Guide-FULL-PREVIEW.html"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":467,"output":125,"cacheRead":71680,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":72272,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1777688029225,"responseId":"064490dd24c457e1c9bf55f84d9d8241"}}
{"type":"message","id":"12a10d04","parentId":"2def6dc6","timestamp":"2026-05-02T02:13:53.010Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_wk3g3jvuvgwt_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"<div class=\"content-page\">\n  <div class=\"section-accent-bar\"></div>\n\n  <div class=\"chapter-header\">\n    <div class=\"chapter-label\">Section 1</div>\n    <h1>What is <span>OpenClaw?</span></h1>\n    <p class=\"chapter-subtitle\">OpenClaw turned my MacBook into a real workhorse.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <h2>Why I Wrote This Guide</h2>\n  <p>I spent weeks figuring OpenClaw out on my own. Googling errors, watching YouTube videos, reading half-finished docs, starting over multiple times. There wasn't one place that said \"hey, here's exactly how to go from zero to having your own AI assistant running your life.\"</p>\n  <p>So I built that place. This guide is everything I learned, everything I wish someone had told me, and everything I actually use day to day. No fluff, no theory — just real world, from someone who isn't a coder.</p>\n  <p>If you're working full time and want an AI assistant that actually works for you — not just for fun experiments — this guide is for you.</p>\n\n  <h2>Before OpenClaw vs. After</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout info\">\n    <div class=\"callout-title\"><span class=\"icon\">📉</span> Before</div>\n    <p>Every morning started the same way — I'd open my phone, check the weather, scroll through emails, check my calendar, look up what I had coming up. It was manual. Repetitive. And by the time I was done with all that, my brain was already tired before I even started working.</p>\n    <p style=\"margin-top:10px\">I'd forget things. Appointments I'd lose track of. Bills I'd almost miss. Follow-ups that slipped through the cracks. I was managing my life with sticky notes and memory and anxiety.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout tip\">\n    <div class=\"callout-title\"><span class=\"icon\">📈</span> After</div>\n    <p>I wake up and OpenClaw has already checked everything — my weather, my calendar, what's coming up today, any urgent emails. By the time I sit down, I'm already informed. No scrolling, no checking, no friction.</p>\n    <p style=\"margin-top:10px\">It reminds me. It checks things. It handles the tracking so I don't have to hold it all in my head. My bills get tracked. My schedule gets monitored. The mental load shifted off my shoulders and onto the system.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <h2>What OpenClaw Actually Does</h2>\n  <p>Here's what that means in practice:</p>\n\n  <h3>It creates and manages files.</h3>\n  <p>Instead of just opening folders, OpenClaw builds them, organizes them, renames them, cleans them up. It handles my storage intelligently instead of me manually dragging files around. I tell it what I want, it figures out where it goes.</p>\n\n  <h3>It runs automations.</h3>\n  <p>Things that used to take manual effort every single day — like a morning briefing on what's ahead, what's coming up, what the weather looks like — now happen automatically. I wake up and the information is already there. No prompting, no asking. It just happens.</p>\n\n  <h3>It builds things without code.</h3>\n  <p>This one's huge. I don't know how to code, but OpenClaw can help me create apps — personal tools for myself or even public ones people can actually use. That's not something most people can do without hiring a developer.</p>\n\n  <h3>It's always on.</h3>\n  <p>Unlike ChatGPT where you open it, ask a question, close it, OpenClaw lives in your system. It monitors, it reminds, it checks, it coordinates — throughout the day, not just when you talk to it.</p>\n\n  <h3>It's saved me time and reduced my mental load.</h3>\n  <p>Things I used to have to track in my head — appointments, follow-ups, reminders, daily check-ins — OpenClaw handles that. I free up brain space for the things I actually want to focus on.</p>\n\n  <h2>What OpenClaw is NOT</h2>\n  <p>I want to be straight with you here, because there's a lot of hype around AI tools right now.</p>\n  <p>OpenClaw is <strong>not</strong> magic. It won't read your mind. It won't do things you haven't taught it to do. And it won't work perfectly the first time you set it up — there's a learning curve.</p>\n  <p>It's also not a chatbot you just \"talk to sometimes.\" The real power comes from building automations and workflows that run on their own. The more you put into setting it up and teaching it, the more you get out of it.</p>\n  <p>And honestly? It's not for everyone. If you don't want to spend any time learning how it works, you'll get frustrated. But if you're willing to spend even a little time building your setup, it's one of the most powerful tools you can have.</p>\n\n  <h2>My Agent Team — A Real Example</h2>\n  <p>One of the most powerful things about OpenClaw is the agent system. I didn't know how to code. I didn't have a technical background. But I built a team — entirely with OpenClaw — that runs alongside me every day.</p>\n\n  <div class=\"key-takeaway\">\n    <div class=\"label\">My Team</div>\n    <p><strong>Dean</strong> 🤖🦞 — coordinates everything and routes work to the right specialist<br>\n    <strong>Emmy</strong> 🦋📧 — handles my emails. Inbox zero, important messages flagged<br>\n    <strong>Finn</strong> 🧊💸 — manages my finances. Tracks bills, monitors cash position<br>\n\n[576 more lines in file. Use offset=640 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1777688033010}}
{"type":"message","id":"5f19bd24","parentId":"12a10d04","timestamp":"2026-05-02T02:14:22.275Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Ah I see - the full preview HTML doesn't have the \"Story Behind OpenClaw\" section with Peter Steinberger's background. That content is only in the Section-1-What-is-OpenClaw.md file, but it wasn't included in the FULL-PREVIEW.html. I need to add it to the HTML.\n\nThe \"What Is OpenClaw?\" section in the HTML starts right with \"Why I Wrote This Guide\" - it skips the intro explanation of what OpenClaw is, the story behind it, etc. The actual markdown file has more content that wasn't ported over.\n\nLet me add the \"Story Behind OpenClaw\" section (with Peter Steinberger's background) into the HTML, right after the chapter header and before \"Why I Wrote This Guide.\"\n","thinkingSignature":"418086a6b511dafc9f8949ad855a5fd15c14088a5e101cf934a589d95e7b5541"},{"type":"text","text":"\n\nFound the issue — **the HTML is missing that whole section**. The markdown file has the Peter Steinberger backstory but it was never added to the HTML preview. Let me add it now.\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_ohdr6pza85iz_1","name":"edit","arguments":{"edits":[{"newText":"  <div class=\"chapter-header\">\n    <div class=\"chapter-label\">Section 1</div>\n    <h1>What is <span>OpenClaw?</span></h1>\n    <p class=\"chapter-subtitle\">OpenClaw turned my MacBook into a real workhorse.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <h2>The Story Behind OpenClaw</h2>\n  <p>OpenClaw was created by <strong>Peter Steinberger</strong> — an Austrian developer who spent 13 years building <strong>PSPDFKit</strong>, a PDF company that ended up powering document handling on over a <strong>billion devices</strong>. We're talking Apple, Dropbox, all the big players. In 2023, he sold that company for reportedly around <strong>€100 million</strong>. By all accounts, he made it. He was done. Retired.</p>\n  <p>Except... he wasn't really done. He was <em>burned out</em>.</p>\n  <p>\"I felt like Austin Powers where they suck the mojo out,\" Peter told Lex Fridman in an interview. \"I couldn't get code out anymore. I was just, like, staring and feeling empty.\"</p>\n  <p>So he did what any burnt-out tech millionaire would do — he traveled. Partied. Tried therapy. Nothing stuck. He was looking for meaning and couldn't find it.</p>\n  <p>Then in April 2025, something changed. He was tinkering with a Twitter analysis tool and realized AI had shifted. The tools could finally handle the boring parts of coding, leaving him free to just <em>build</em>. So he got back in the game.</p>\n  <p>He built the first prototype of OpenClaw in just <strong>one hour</strong>. His 44th AI project since 2009. And he created it for the simplest reason possible — \"I was annoyed that it didn't exist, so I just prompted it into existence.\"</p>\n  <p>The project went through a few names before settling on OpenClaw. First it was Clawdbot, then Moltbot, then OpenClaw — all because of naming disputes with other companies. (Anthropic had trademark issues with \"Molt.\") It launched quietly in late 2025 and then... exploded.</p>\n  <p>We're talking <strong>2 million visitors in a single week</strong>. Over <strong>180,000 GitHub stars</strong> in just a few weeks. One of the fastest-growing open-source projects in history.</p>\n  <p>Peter caught the attention of every big player in tech. <strong>Sam Altman</strong> called him a genius. <strong>Mark Zuckerberg</strong> personally reached out to recruit him. <strong>OpenAI hired him</strong> in February 2026. But here's the thing — Peter made sure OpenClaw stayed open-source and community-driven, moving it into an independent foundation supported by OpenAI. He didn't sell out.</p>\n  <p>\"I don't do this for the money,\" he told Fridman. \"I want to have fun and have impact.\"</p>\n  <p>That's the vibe behind OpenClaw. It's not some corporate AI tool. It's a side project from a developer who was bored and wanted to build something useful. And it grew into something that changed how a lot of us think about what our computers can actually do.</p>\n\n  <h2>Why I Wrote This Guide</h2>","oldText":"  <div class=\"chapter-header\">\n    <div class=\"chapter-label\">Section 1</div>\n    <h1>What is <span>OpenClaw?</span></h1>\n    <p class=\"chapter-subtitle\">OpenClaw turned my MacBook into a real workhorse.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <h2>Why I Wrote This Guide</h2>"}],"path":"/Users/bobbygalletta/Desktop/OpenClaw/OpenClaw-Guide-By-Bobby/The-OpenClaw-Guide-FULL-PREVIEW.html"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":1434,"output":1142,"cacheRead":72128,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":74704,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1777688033011,"responseId":"064490e15d71fb843831ce3628e2e7f6"}}
{"type":"message","id":"76692172","parentId":"5f19bd24","timestamp":"2026-05-02T02:14:24.029Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_ohdr6pza85iz_1","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced 1 block(s) in /Users/bobbygalletta/Desktop/OpenClaw/OpenClaw-Guide-By-Bobby/The-OpenClaw-Guide-FULL-PREVIEW.html."}],"details":{"diff":"      ...\n  585     <h1>What is <span>OpenClaw?</span></h1>\n  586     <p class=\"chapter-subtitle\">OpenClaw turned my MacBook into a real workhorse.</p>\n  587   </div>\n  588 \n+ 589   <h2>The Story Behind OpenClaw</h2>\n+ 590   <p>OpenClaw was created by <strong>Peter Steinberger</strong> — an Austrian developer who spent 13 years building <strong>PSPDFKit</strong>, a PDF company that ended up powering document handling on over a <strong>billion devices</strong>. We're talking Apple, Dropbox, all the big players. In 2023, he sold that company for reportedly around <strong>€100 million</strong>. By all accounts, he made it. He was done. Retired.</p>\n+ 591   <p>Except... he wasn't really done. He was <em>burned out</em>.</p>\n+ 592   <p>\"I felt like Austin Powers where they suck the mojo out,\" Peter told Lex Fridman in an interview. \"I couldn't get code out anymore. I was just, like, staring and feeling empty.\"</p>\n+ 593   <p>So he did what any burnt-out tech millionaire would do — he traveled. Partied. Tried therapy. Nothing stuck. He was looking for meaning and couldn't find it.</p>\n+ 594   <p>Then in April 2025, something changed. He was tinkering with a Twitter analysis tool and realized AI had shifted. The tools could finally handle the boring parts of coding, leaving him free to just <em>build</em>. So he got back in the game.</p>\n+ 595   <p>He built the first prototype of OpenClaw in just <strong>one hour</strong>. His 44th AI project since 2009. And he created it for the simplest reason possible — \"I was annoyed that it didn't exist, so I just prompted it into existence.\"</p>\n+ 596   <p>The project went through a few names before settling on OpenClaw. First it was Clawdbot, then Moltbot, then OpenClaw — all because of naming disputes with other companies. (Anthropic had trademark issues with \"Molt.\") It launched quietly in late 2025 and then... exploded.</p>\n+ 597   <p>We're talking <strong>2 million visitors in a single week</strong>. Over <strong>180,000 GitHub stars</strong> in just a few weeks. One of the fastest-growing open-source projects in history.</p>\n+ 598   <p>Peter caught the attention of every big player in tech. <strong>Sam Altman</strong> called him a genius. <strong>Mark Zuckerberg</strong> personally reached out to recruit him. <strong>OpenAI hired him</strong> in February 2026. But here's the thing — Peter made sure OpenClaw stayed open-source and community-driven, moving it into an independent foundation supported by OpenAI. He didn't sell out.</p>\n+ 599   <p>\"I don't do this for the money,\" he told Fridman. \"I want to have fun and have impact.\"</p>\n+ 600   <p>That's the vibe behind OpenClaw. It's not some corporate AI tool. It's a side project from a developer who was bored and wanted to build something useful. And it grew into something that changed how a lot of us think about what our computers can actually do.</p>\n+ 601 \n  589   <h2>Why I Wrote This Guide</h2>\n  590   <p>I spent weeks figuring OpenClaw out on my own. Googling errors, watching YouTube videos, reading half-finished docs, starting over multiple times. There wasn't one place that said \"hey, here's exactly how to go from zero to having your own AI assistant running your life.\"</p>\n  591   <p>So I built that place. This guide is everything I learned, everything I wish someone had told me, and everything I actually use day to day. No fluff, no theory — just real world, from someone who isn't a coder.</p>\n  592   <p>If you're working full time and want an AI assistant that actually works for you — not just for fun experiments — this guide is for you.</p>\n      ...","firstChangedLine":589},"isError":false,"timestamp":1777688064029}}
{"type":"message","id":"d0a5000c","parentId":"76692172","timestamp":"2026-05-02T02:14:31.525Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Done. I added the \"The Story Behind OpenClaw\" section right after the chapter header, before \"Why I Wrote This Guide\". Bobby can now refresh Safari and find it easily as a distinct section with a heading.\n","thinkingSignature":"5abbc90d95bcf2951cb4dbd61b3aaf0f3ba8b288fa64321896ccee22e55191e8"},{"type":"text","text":"\n\nDone! I added **\"The Story Behind OpenClaw\"** as its own section heading right after the chapter header — before \"Why I Wrote This Guide.\" Refresh Safari and it'll be right at the top of Section 1, easy to find. Let me know if you want to adjust the wording or add anything!"}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":1023,"output":115,"cacheRead":73536,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":74674,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1777688064036,"responseId":"0644910087e0d52345b8b2fafc5e401b"}}
