{"type":"message","id":"c104167d","parentId":"9f647c0c","timestamp":"2026-05-02T02:37:25.024Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_6recmeinalho_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# OpenClaw Guide by Bobby G.\n\n*A practical, real-world guide to OpenClaw — written by someone who uses it daily.*\n\n---\n\n## Section 1: What is OpenClaw?\n\n### What Is OpenClaw?\n\nOpenClaw is an **autonomous AI agent** that runs on your computer — think of it like having a digital employee who lives on your MacBook. It's always working, always monitoring, always ready to help. Unlike ChatGPT where you open it, ask a question, close it, and it's gone — OpenClaw stays running in the background. It checks your email, manages your files, runs automations, sends you updates, and handles all the repetitive stuff you'd otherwise have to do yourself.\n\nHere's what makes it different from other AI tools:\n\n**It's local.** OpenClaw runs on your own machine, not in some distant data center. Your data stays on your computer. Your memories are stored in simple text files you can actually read and understand. It's not locking your life into someone else's cloud.\n\n**It's always on.** It doesn't wait for you to ask. It monitors, reminds, checks, and coordinates throughout the day. You set up workflows once, and they run on their own — every morning you wake up informed, every evening you get an update, without lifting a finger.\n\n**It's built around open-source.** OpenClaw started as a side project from one developer, and it grew into one of the fastest-growing open-source projects in history. It's not owned by a big tech company trying to lock you into their ecosystem.\n\n**It works with tools you already use.** Email, calendar, reminders, files, browsers, messaging apps — OpenClaw connects to them all and automates the work between them.\n\n---\n\n### The Story Behind OpenClaw\n\nOpenClaw was created by **Peter Steinberger**, an Austrian developer who spent 13 years building **PSPDFKit** — a PDF company that ended up powering document handling on over a billion devices. We're talking Apple, Dropbox, all the big players. In 2023, he sold that company for reportedly around $110 million. By all accounts, he made it. He was done. Retired.\n\nExcept... he wasn't really done. He was *burned out*.\n\n\"I felt like Austin Powers where they suck the mojo out,\" Peter told Lex Fridman in an interview. \"I couldn't get code out anymore. I was just, like, staring and feeling empty.\"\n\nSo he did what any burnt-out tech millionaire would do — he traveled. Partied. Tried therapy. Nothing stuck. He was looking for meaning and couldn't find it.\n\nThen in April 2025, something changed. He was tinkering with a Twitter analysis tool and realized AI had shifted. The tools could finally handle the boring parts of coding, leaving him free to just *build*. So he got back in the game.\n\nHe built the first prototype of OpenClaw in just **one hour**. His 44th AI project since 2009. And he created it for the simplest reason possible — \"I was annoyed that it didn't exist, so I just prompted it into existence.\"\n\nThe project went through a few names before settling on OpenClaw. First it was Clawdbot, then Moltbot, then OpenClaw — all because of naming disputes with other companies. (Anthropic had trademark issues with \"Molt.\") It launched quietly in late 2025 and then... exploded.\n\nWe're talking 2 million visitors in a single week. Over 180,000 GitHub stars in just a few weeks. One of the fastest-growing open-source projects in history.\n\nPeter caught the attention of every big player in tech. **Sam Altman** called him a genius. **Mark Zuckerberg** personally reached out to recruit him. **OpenAI hired him** in February 2026. But here's the thing — Peter made sure OpenClaw stayed open-source and community-driven, moving it into an independent foundation supported by OpenAI. He didn't sell out.\n\n\"I don't do this for the money,\" he told Fridman. \"I want to have fun and have impact.\"\n\nThat's the vibe behind OpenClaw. It's not some corporate AI tool. It's a side project from a developer who was bored and wanted to build something useful. And it grew into something that changed how a lot of us think about what our computers can actually do.\n\n---\n\n### Why I Wrote This Guide\n\nI spent weeks figuring OpenClaw out on my own. Googling errors, watching YouTube videos, reading half-finished docs, starting over multiple times. There wasn't one place that said \"hey, here's exactly how to go from zero to having your own AI assistant running your life.\"\n\nSo I built that place. This guide is everything I learned, everything I wish someone had told me, and everything I actually use day to day. No fluff, no theory — just real world, from someone who isn't a coder.\n\nIf you're working full time and want an AI assistant that actually works for you — not just for fun experiments — this guide is for you.\n\n---\n\n### Before OpenClaw vs. After\n\n**Before:**\nEvery morning started the same way — I'd open my phone, check the weather, scroll through emails, check my calendar, look up what I had coming up. It was manual. Repetitive. And by the time I was done with all that, my brain was already tired before I even started working.\n\nI'd forget things. Appointments I'd lose track of. Bills I'd almost miss. Follow-ups that slipped through the cracks. I was managing my life with sticky notes and memory and anxiety.\n\nMy files were a mess. Downloads went somewhere, I never knew where. Everything was scattered.\n\n**After:**\nI wake up and OpenClaw has already checked everything — my weather, my calendar, what's coming up today, any urgent emails. By the time I sit down, I'm already informed. No scrolling, no checking, no friction.\n\nIt reminds me. It checks things. It handles the tracking so I don't have to hold it all in my head. My bills get tracked. My schedule gets monitored. The mental load shifted off my shoulders and onto the system.\n\n---\n\n### What OpenClaw Actually Does\n\nHere's what that means in practice:\n\n**It creates and manages files.**\nInstead of just opening folders, OpenClaw builds them, organizes them, renames them, cleans them up. It handles my storage intelligently instead of me manually dragging files around. I tell it what I want, it figures out where it goes.\n\n**It runs automations.**\nThings that used to take manual effort every single day — like a morning briefing on what's ahead, what's coming up, what the weather looks like — now happen automatically. I wake up and the information is already there. No prompting, no asking. It just happens.\n\n**It builds things without code.**\nThis one's huge. I don't know how to code, but OpenClaw can help me create apps — personal tools for myself or even public ones people can actually use. That's not something most people can do without hiring a developer.\n\n**It's always on.**\nUnlike ChatGPT where you open it, ask a question, close it, OpenClaw lives in your system. It monitors, it reminds, it checks, it coordinates — throughout the day, not just when you talk to it.\n\n**It's saved me time and reduced my mental load.**\nThings I used to have to track in my head — appointments, follow-ups, reminders, daily check-ins — OpenClaw handles that. I free up brain space for the things I actually want to focus on.\n\n---\n\n### What OpenClaw is NOT\n\nI want to be straight with you here, because there's a lot of hype around AI tools right now.\n\nOpenClaw is **not** magic. It won't read your mind. It won't do things you haven't taught it to do. And it won't work perfectly the first time you set it up — there's a learning curve.\n\nIt's also not a chatbot you just \"talk to sometimes.\" The real power comes from building automations and workflows that run on their own. The more you put into setting it up and teaching it, the more you get out of it.\n\nAnd honestly? It's not for everyone. If you don't want to spend any time learning how it works, you'll get frustrated. But if you're willing to spend even a little time building your setup, it's one of the most powerful tools you can have.\n\n---\n\n### My Agent Team — A Real Example of What OpenClaw Can Do\n\nOne of the most powerful things about OpenClaw is the agent system. I didn't know how to code. I didn't have a technical background. But I built a team — entirely with OpenClaw — that runs alongside me every day.\n\nHere's my team:\n\n- **Dean** 🤖🦞 — that's me. I coordinate everything and route work to the right specialist.\n- **Emmy** 🦋📧 — handles my emails. Inbox zero, important messages flagged, everything organized.\n- **Finn** 🧊💸 — manages my finances. Tracks bills, monitors my cash position, keeps me on budget.\n- **Agent X** ⚡🕶️ — runs my X/Twitter. Posts, engages, keeps my presence active.\n- **YoYo** 🎥✨ — manages my YouTube. Content ideas, uploads, channel management.\n- **Rex** 🔍📊 — does deep research on topics I need to understand quickly.\n- **Cody** 🧑‍💻 — builds tools and apps. If I need something built, Cody creates it.\n- **DJ** 🎧 — handles music and audio needs.\n- **Reese** 🍳 — helps in the kitchen with recipes and meal planning.\n\nEvery morning, Dean sends me a briefing. Every evening, I get a financial update. When I need something, I tell Dean and he routes it to whoever needs to handle it.\n\nThis isn't science fiction. It's not something I hired a developer to build. I set it up myself, piece by piece, using OpenClaw.\n\nAnd that's what this guide is really about — showing you what's possible so you can build your own version.\n\n---\n\n### What Surprised Me Most\n\nI'll be real — there were things I didn't expect.\n\n**That I could actually build apps.** I didn't know how to code. I still don't. But I built a working app from scratch using OpenClaw. That still trips me out a little.\n\n**That it actually remembered things.** Not just in the moment, but long-term. Files I created months ago, decisions I made, preferences I forgot I even had — it all stuck around.\n\n**How much clearer my head felt.** This sounds weird, but once I had a system that could track things for me, my brain stopped trying to hold it all. That mental clarity is harder to quantify but just as valuable as the time it saves.\n\n**How fast it became second nature.** Within a week, I wasn't thinking about it anymore. I was just asking. \"Hey, add that to the list.\" \"Remind me about that tomorrow.\" It just worked.\n\n---\n\n*More sections coming soon...*"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1777689445023}}
