{"type":"message","id":"35d29236","parentId":"bea4cc07","timestamp":"2026-05-02T03:11:31.078Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_4p3mmvsrhhb5_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"=== Section-8-Real-World-Workflows.md ===\nDon't try to set up all six of these at once. Pick the one that most directly relates to what you're trying to build right now:\n\n- **Building a YouTube channel?** → Start with Workflow 1 (Research Pipeline)\n- **Already making videos?** → Add Workflow 2 (Script Writing) to speed up production\n- **Want to get more mileage from content?** → Add Workflow 3 (Repurposing Machine)\n- **Building a personal brand?** → Start with Workflow 4 (Personal Brand Management)\n- **Serious about YouTube operations?** → Set up Workflow 5 (Multi-Agent Pipeline)\n- **Music career?** → Start with Workflow 6 (Music & Brand Building)\n\nMaster one, add the next. Build your system piece by piece. That's how you actually make this work long-term.\n=== Section-9-Advanced-Techniques.md ===\nDon't try to implement everything at once. Pick one technique from this section and go deep on it this week:\n\n- **Week 1:** Do a full brain dump and expectation setting session\n- **Week 2:** Practice reverse prompting for every task\n- **Week 3:** Build your first custom tool (task board, CRM, etc.)\n- **Week 4:** Set up your second agent and start running a two-agent pipeline\n\nThese techniques compound. Each one you master makes the others more powerful. The goal isn't to implement all of them — it's to make them part of how you naturally work with OpenClaw.\n\nOnce you've internalized the mindset, you stop thinking about \"what should I ask OpenClaw to do?\" and start thinking \"what should be happening automatically?\" That's when OpenClaw stops being a tool and starts being a team member.\n=== Section-10-Money-Making-Use-Cases.md ===\n- Set up your first multi-agent pipeline if you're ready\n\n**This year:**\n- Choose your primary money path and go deep on it\n- Build an audience or client base around your work\n- Use OpenClaw to amplify everything you do\n\nThe guide ends here, but the work is just starting. OpenClaw is a tool that rewards action. The people who get the most out of it are the ones who actually use it — every day, consistently, while constantly looking for new ways to let it amplify what they're doing.\n\nGo build something. OpenClaw is on your team now."}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":531,"aggregated":"=== Section-8-Real-World-Workflows.md ===\nDon't try to set up all six of these at once. Pick the one that most directly relates to what you're trying to build right now:\n\n- **Building a YouTube channel?** → Start with Workflow 1 (Research Pipeline)\n- **Already making videos?** → Add Workflow 2 (Script Writing) to speed up production\n- **Want to get more mileage from content?** → Add Workflow 3 (Repurposing Machine)\n- **Building a personal brand?** → Start with Workflow 4 (Personal Brand Management)\n- **Serious about YouTube operations?** → Set up Workflow 5 (Multi-Agent Pipeline)\n- **Music career?** → Start with Workflow 6 (Music & Brand Building)\n\nMaster one, add the next. Build your system piece by piece. That's how you actually make this work long-term.\n=== Section-9-Advanced-Techniques.md ===\nDon't try to implement everything at once. Pick one technique from this section and go deep on it this week:\n\n- **Week 1:** Do a full brain dump and expectation setting session\n- **Week 2:** Practice reverse prompting for every task\n- **Week 3:** Build your first custom tool (task board, CRM, etc.)\n- **Week 4:** Set up your second agent and start running a two-agent pipeline\n\nThese techniques compound. Each one you master makes the others more powerful. The goal isn't to implement all of them — it's to make them part of how you naturally work with OpenClaw.\n\nOnce you've internalized the mindset, you stop thinking about \"what should I ask OpenClaw to do?\" and start thinking \"what should be happening automatically?\" That's when OpenClaw stops being a tool and starts being a team member.\n=== Section-10-Money-Making-Use-Cases.md ===\n- Set up your first multi-agent pipeline if you're ready\n\n**This year:**\n- Choose your primary money path and go deep on it\n- Build an audience or client base around your work\n- Use OpenClaw to amplify everything you do\n\nThe guide ends here, but the work is just starting. OpenClaw is a tool that rewards action. The people who get the most out of it are the ones who actually use it — every day, consistently, while constantly looking for new ways to let it amplify what they're doing.\n\nGo build something. OpenClaw is on your team now.","cwd":"/Users/bobbygalletta/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1777691491078}}
{"type":"message","id":"e6478913","parentId":"35d29236","timestamp":"2026-05-02T03:11:48.895Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have the actual truth. Sections 8, 9, and 10 DO have full content in the .md files - 257, 256, and 253 lines respectively, all ending properly without placeholder text. The sub-agent report was accurate. Bobby's confusion was valid - the HTML preview file just wasn't updated to show the real content.\n\nSo the issue is:\n1. The .md source files have complete, proper content for sections 8, 9, 10\n2. The HTML preview still shows DRAFT placeholders - it was never updated with the real content\n\nWhat I need to do is build out the HTML preview to include sections 8, 9, 10 from the source markdown files. This is a bigger task than just a few edits.\n\n\nI should clarify with Bobby that the actual content exists - it just needs to be transferred into the HTML preview file. This is the disconnect: the sub-agent reported accurately that the content was complete, but the HTML file never got updated to reflect that.\n","thinkingSignature":"f81ea7d0ba9178f1e6fc3e6b422f3ebf952fe20de3c9bd6e7dcca42cbb567cc3"},{"type":"text","text":"\n\nYou're right to be confused — but here's what I actually found when I checked directly:\n\n**The .md source files ARE complete:**\n- Section 8 (Real-World Workflows) — 257 lines, proper ending\n- Section 9 (Advanced Techniques) — 256 lines, proper ending\n- Section 10 (Money-Making Use Cases) — 253 lines, proper ending\n\nThey all end correctly — no placeholder text.\n\n**The HTML preview is what's broken.** It was never updated with the actual content for Sections 8-10. It still shows DRAFT placeholders while the real content sits in the .md files.\n\nSo the content is there — it just needs to be pulled into the HTML. That's the disconnect between what exists and what you see in Safari.\n\n**What I need to do now:** Build Sections 8, 9, and 10 into the HTML file using the actual content from the .md source files. That's a bigger rebuild than the small edits we've been doing.\n\nWant me to do that? I'll replace the DRAFT placeholders with the real content from Sections 8, 9, and 10."}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":630,"output":446,"cacheRead":90944,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":92020,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1777691491081,"responseId":"06449e6318f670f78e089f443c7ba216"}}
